# n8n-decanter â€” guide for coding agents

This is the **source of truth** for working in this repository, and it is written to
be tool-agnostic. Codex and opencode read this file natively; Claude Code reads it
through a one-line `@AGENTS.md` import in `CLAUDE.md`; other agents can be pointed at
this file directly. Keep project-specific rules here so every agent stays in sync.

This repo holds n8n workflows *decanted* into git-friendly form: one folder per
workflow containing `workflow.json` plus a `code/` subdir with one source file
per Code node. The
`n8n-decanter` CLI moves content between here and the live n8n instance
(`pull` / `push`). This document is the contract for creating and editing these files.

## The short version

- **Code lives in `code/`, never in `workflow.json`.** A node's `jsCode` is only
  a `//@file:code/<name>` placeholder â€” edit the file it points at.
- **Never hand-edit `.decanter.json` or a `*.remote.js`, and never write a
  `// @ts-n8n sha256:` marker.** These are machine-owned; touching them corrupts
  sync state and the CLI blocks it at `push`.
- **Structural edits have verbs â€” use them instead of hand-editing JSON:**
  `node create` a Code node, `node rename` a node, `rename` a workflow,
  `create`/`duplicate` a workflow. Each does the fiddly multi-file edit
  atomically and re-validates the folder.
- **`push` is a deploy to the live instance â€” only when the user asks.** Edit,
  then verify offline with `n8n-decanter check` and `n8n-decanter node run`.

The rest of this document is the full contract behind those four points.

## How this differs from standard n8n editing â€” read this first

Your general n8n knowledge (docs, n8n MCP tools, training data) is **valid** for:
node types and parameters, expression syntax, connection semantics, the Code-node
runtime. It is **wrong** about how code is stored here. The deviations:

1. **`jsCode` in `workflow.json` never contains code.** Its entire value is a
   placeholder: `//@file:code/<filename>`
   (e.g. `"jsCode": "//@file:code/amazon-feed.ts"`).
   Never inline JavaScript into `workflow.json`; edit the referenced file.
2. **Code node sources live in the folder's `code/` subdir**, named after the
   node in kebab-case (`Amazon Feed` â†’ `code/amazon-feed.ts`). `.js` files are
   pushed verbatim (what you write is exactly what runs in n8n). `.ts` files
   are compiled on push; the local `.ts` is the only source of truth â€” n8n
   holds compiled output.
3. **Never write a `// @ts-n8n sha256:â€¦` line.** That marker is appended by the
   tool to *compiled* output on push. It must not appear in any repo file.
4. **`.decanter.json` is machine state** (node-id â†’ filename map, drift-detection
   hashes). Never edit it by hand; never "fix" a hash.
5. **`code/<node>.remote.js` is an incoming-change artifact** written by `pull` when
   someone edited a TS-managed node in the n8n UI. Handle it like an incoming
   diff: port the change into the `.ts`, delete the `.remote.js`, then the user
   pushes. Never edit `.remote.js` itself; never push while one exists.
6. **Renames have no UI magic here.** The n8n editor auto-updates references on
   rename; editing files does not. Use `n8n-decanter node rename <workflow>` â€” it
   rewrites every reference atomically. See "Renaming a node" below.
7. **New workflows are born on the server, not from a repo folder.** There is no
   id-less folder that becomes a workflow on push. Use `n8n-decanter create
   "<name>"` â€” it posts a blank draft to n8n and pulls it back (the server
   assigns the id) â€” `n8n-decanter duplicate <workflow>` to clone an existing
   workflow into a new one, or create it in the n8n UI and `pull`. Then add its
   id to `decanter.config.json`. A created workflow is **unpublished**; `publish`
   takes it live, `unpublish` returns it to draft-only, and `delete <workflow>`
   removes one from the server (the local folder is kept).

> **Enforcement.** Rules 1, 3, 4, 5 are *hard invariants* â€” violating them corrupts
> sync state. They are enforced by the CLI at `push` time regardless of who made the
> edit (any agent, or a human). On Claude Code and opencode they are additionally
> guarded before the write happens (see `.claude/settings.json` and `opencode.json`).
> If a write is blocked with a `decanter-guard` reason, the edit broke a hard rule â€”
> fix the edit, don't work around the guard.

## File ownership

| File | Written by | May the agent edit it? |
|---|---|---|
| `workflow.json` | pull + you | Yes â€” structure, parameters, connections. Placeholders stay placeholders. |
| `code/<node>.js` | pull + you | Yes â€” this is live node code, verbatim. |
| `code/<node>.ts` | you only | Yes â€” pull never touches it. |
| `code/<node>.remote.js` | pull only | No â€” read, port into the `.ts`, delete. |
| `.decanter.json` | tool only | No. |
| `decanter.config.json` | you | Yes â€” add/remove workflow ids. |
| `n8n-globals.d.ts` | you | Yes â€” extend when node code uses a global it doesn't cover yet. |

## Editing `workflow.json`

Pretty-printed, 2-space indent, keep the existing key order (clean diffs are the
point of this repo).

A node object:

```json
{
  "id": "a1b2c3d4-â€¦",            // UUID v4 â€” `n8n-decanter node create <workflow>` mints it; NEVER change an existing id
  "name": "Amazon Feed",          // unique per workflow â€” connections + $('â€¦') reference it
  "type": "n8n-nodes-base.code",
  "typeVersion": 2,
  "position": [880, 300],
  "parameters": {
    "mode": "runOnceForAllItems", // or "runOnceForEachItem"
    "jsCode": "//@file:code/amazon-feed.ts"
  }
}
```

Connections are keyed by **node name**, not id:

```json
"connections": {
  "Fetch Products": { "main": [[{ "node": "Amazon Feed", "type": "main", "index": 0 }]] }
}
```

Rules:

- **Expressions** in parameters keep their `=` prefix: `"={{ $json.sku }}"`.
  A value without `=` is a literal string.
- **Credentials** are referenced as `{ "id": "â€¦", "name": "â€¦" }` and must already
  exist in n8n â€” never invent credential ids.
- **Not synced / don't add:** `active`, `tags`, `pinData`, `shared`, timestamps.
  The push endpoint only accepts `name`, `nodes`, `connections`, `settings`
  (whitelisted keys), `staticData`. Activation is managed in the n8n UI.
- **Position:** keep a sensible grid; new nodes roughly +200 x from their input.

### Renaming a node

Use the verb â€” it rewrites every reference atomically, offline, and re-validates
the folder:

```sh
n8n-decanter node rename <workflow> "<Old Name>" "<New Name>"
```

It touches all four places a rename must hit at once â€” the same four you'd have
to keep in sync **by hand** (and atomically) if you ever edit the raw JSON:

1. `name` in the node object.
2. Every reference in `connections` (keys *and* target `"node"` values).
3. Every `$('Old Name')` in **all** code files of the workflow.
4. The source file name and its `//@file:` placeholder (kebab-case convention,
   file stays in `code/`).

Renaming a **workflow**: `n8n-decanter rename <workflow> "<New Name>"`. The
folder is a stable local slug and is left untouched; the id inside
`workflow.json` is authoritative, and the display name is cached in
`.decanter.json`.

### Adding a Code node

1. `n8n-decanter node create <workflow> "<Node name>" [--ts]` scaffolds it in one
   step: it mints the node `id`, writes the `code/` source (`.js`, or `.ts` with
   `--ts`), adds the `//@file:` placeholder, records it in `.decanter.json`,
   and re-checks the folder. The node lands **disconnected**.
2. Wire it up â€” add its connections in `workflow.json` (and any `$('â€¦')`
   references from other nodes), then edit the source in `code/`.
3. Verify: `n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture.json]` to execute it, then
   `n8n-decanter check` (typecheck + layout).

## Writing Code node code

The runtime contract (identical for `.js` and `.ts` â€” types are erased):

- Code runs as a function body, **top-level `return` required**.
  - `runOnceForAllItems`: return an array of items: `[{ json: {â€¦} }, â€¦]`.
    Always wrap in `{ json: â€¦ }` explicitly.
  - `runOnceForEachItem`: return a single `{ json: {â€¦} }`.
  - Editors squiggle that top-level `return`/`await` (TS1108/TS1375/TS1378) â€”
    a **false positive** from the editor's own tsserver; ignore it, and never
    "fix" it by wrapping the file in a function. `n8n-decanter check` wraps
    node bodies in memory before typechecking and is authoritative.
    The bundled `decanter-ts-plugin/` suppresses exactly these three codes on
    node files (all other diagnostics stay live) once tsserver runs the
    workspace TypeScript: `npm install`, then in VS Code accept
    *Use Workspace Version* (offered via `.vscode/settings.json`'s
    `typescript.tsdk`; JetBrains uses the project TypeScript by default).
- **Available globals: `n8n-globals.d.ts` is the authoritative list.** Open it
  to see every global in scope with its exact signature (`$input`, `$('Node
  Name')`, `$json`, `$binary`, the Luxon `DateTime`/`$now`/`$today`, `$workflow`,
  `$execution`, `$getWorkflowStaticData`, â€¦). If node code needs a global that
  file doesn't declare yet, add it there.
- **Imports**: `.js` nodes â€” none at all (they run verbatim; assume the
  instance allows no external or built-in modules). `.ts` nodes â€” imports
  from inside this repo (`shared/`, relative paths) and from npm packages
  listed in `decanter.config.json`'s `"bundleDependencies"` are **bundled
  into the compiled node on push** (self-contained output, works on any
  instance incl. n8n Cloud). Rules: imports at the **top of the file** only;
  relative paths must stay inside this repo; unlisted npm packages and Node
  builtins (`node:*`, `fs`, `crypto`, â€¦) are compile errors. Never
  `require()`.
- `console.log` is available for debugging (visible in the execution view).
- `$('Node Name')` takes the node's **name** â€” so `rename` keeps it in sync.

### `.js` nodes (default â€” lossless)

What you write is byte-for-byte what runs and what round-trips back on pull.
Type-safety via JSDoc:

```js
// @ts-check

/** @typedef {{ sku: string, qty: number }} StockLine */

/** @type {StockLine[]} */
const lines = [];
for (const item of $input.all()) {
  // â€¦
}
return lines.map((l) => ({ json: l }));
```

- First line is `// @ts-check`.
- Prefer `@typedef` for shapes, inline casts `/** @type {Foo} */ (x)` where
  narrowing is needed. `@template`, `@satisfies` are available.
- Comments are fine and encouraged â€” they survive into n8n and document the
  node in place.

### `.ts` nodes (one-way)

Choose `.ts` when the type surface is heavy (large interfaces, generics,
discriminated unions). Costs, so you can weigh them:

- esbuild compiles on push: **comments are stripped** and **line numbers shift**
  â€” n8n error line numbers won't match the source, and the node code in the
  n8n UI is undocumented output. Documentation belongs in the `.ts`.
- UI edits can't be merged back automatically (they arrive as `.remote.js`).

Rules: full TS is fine (interfaces, type aliases, enums, generics); still
ends in a top-level `return`. Never commit compiled output; never add the
marker line.

**Shared code (`shared/`)**: put helpers and types used by several nodes in
`shared/*.ts` and import them from `.ts` nodes â€” types *and* functions:

```ts
import { total, type OrderLine } from "../../shared/money";

const lines: OrderLine[] = $input.all().map((i) => i.json as OrderLine);
return [{ json: { total: total(lines) } }];
```

Push inlines the imported code into the compiled node (each importing node
carries its own copy â€” keep helpers small). Editing a shared file makes every
importing node show up as "push pending" in `status`; push to propagate.
Small npm libraries work the same way once installed here (`npm i zod`) and
opted in via `"bundleDependencies": ["zod"]` in `decanter.config.json` â€”
pure-JS packages only (no native addons, no builtins). `.js` nodes cannot
import; give them JSDoc `@typedef`s or convert to `.ts`.

### Switching a node `.js` â†’ `.ts` (or back)

1. Rename the file, convert JSDoc â†” annotations.
2. Update the `//@file:` placeholder in `workflow.json`.
3. `n8n-decanter check`. The tool picks up the new extension on next push;
   direction of sync changes accordingly (`.ts` = one-way).

## Verification

Two offline tools, always available (no credentials, no network, no live n8n):

- **`n8n-decanter check`** â€” runs the layout-compliance guard *and* the
  typecheck (the same wrapper that maps top-level-`return` node bodies back to
  real line numbers). Run it after editing any code file or `n8n-globals.d.ts`;
  treat a failure as a blocker. `npm run typecheck` is an alias for it.
- **`n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture.json]`** â€” actually executes a node's body
  against a faked n8n context (`$input`, `$json`, `$('Node')`, `DateTime`, â€¦) and
  prints the items it returns. Prefer this over hand-rolling a throwaway test
  script.
  - The optional fixture JSON supplies the context; every field is optional:

    ```json
    {
      "input":  [{ "json": { "sku": "A1" } }],
      "nodes":  { "Fetch Products": [{ "json": { "id": 1 } }] },
      "env":    { "REGION": "eu" },
      "staticData": { "global": { "cursor": 42 } }
    }
    ```

    `input` feeds `$input`/`$json`; `nodes` backs `$('Node Name')`; without a
    fixture the input defaults to a single empty item. `env` backs `$env`,
    which is **empty by default** (like n8n's scoped `$env`) â€” set it here, or
    pass `--allow-env` to inherit the process environment (may include
    `N8N_API_KEY`; never `run --allow-env` an untrusted node).
    `$getWorkflowStaticData` is seeded from `workflow.json`'s `staticData`
    (`global` and this node's `node:` slice); a fixture `staticData` replaces
    the matching slice (`"node"` = the node being run). Mutations are visible
    during the run but never persisted â€” `run` is offline.
  - Run mode (`runOnceForAllItems` / `runOnceForEachItem`) is read from the node
    in `workflow.json`, so each-item nodes are looped once per input item.
- JSON validity of `workflow.json` after every structural edit.

## Real execution data (`executions/` â€” temporary, gitignored)

When you need to see what data actually flows through a workflow â€” to write an
accurate `node run` fixture, or to debug a node against real payloads â€” fetch
recent executions from the instance instead of guessing shapes:

```sh
n8n-decanter executions "<workflow>"                    # 5 most recent, full run data
n8n-decanter executions "<workflow>" --status=error --limit=3
n8n-decanter executions 4711                            # one execution by its id
```

Each execution lands as `workflows/<folder>/executions/<execId>.json`. The items
a node produced are under
`data.resultData.runData["<Node Name>"][0].data.main[0][]` â€” each entry's
`.json` is one item, exactly what `$('<Node Name>')` (and the downstream node's
`$input`) sees at runtime. Copy real item shapes from here into `node run` fixtures.

Rules:

- **Temporary working data, never committed.** The tool writes the dir
  self-ignoring (`executions/.gitignore` containing `*`) because run data can
  hold credentials and PII â€” never weaken that, and never copy secrets from it
  into code or fixtures.
- **Clean up when the task that needed it is done:**
  `n8n-decanter executions clean` (offline; removes every `executions/` dir,
  or pass a workflow ref to scope it).
- **Convenience, not ground truth.** Executions run the *published* workflow
  version (n8n 2.x), which may be older than the local draft, and payloads
  change over time â€” re-fetch rather than trusting stale files.

## Commands â€” who runs what

- **Offline, safe â€” run freely:** `n8n-decanter check` (or `npm run typecheck`),
  `n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture]`, `n8n-decanter node create <workflow> "<Node name>"`,
  `n8n-decanter node rename <workflow> â€¦`, `n8n-decanter rename <workflow> â€¦`,
  `n8n-decanter executions clean`. These never touch the network.
- **Reads remote, no writes:** `n8n-decanter status` (`--diff` shows the line
  diffs; exits 1 on conflict/remote drift) and `n8n-decanter executions <workflow>`
  (fetches execution data, read-only) â€” safe to run, but they do contact the
  instance.
- **Live n8n instance â€” only when the user explicitly asks:** `n8n-decanter
  pull` / `push` / `watch` read/write the real instance and `push` deploys;
  `create "<name>"` adds a new workflow and `duplicate <workflow>` clones an existing
  one into a new (unpublished) remote workflow, and `publish` / `unpublish`
  change what is live (`publish` takes the draft live immediately, `unpublish`
  returns it to draft-only). Otherwise finish edits, verify with `check` +
  `run`, and report that the change is ready to push (or publish).
- **Destructive â€” never without an explicit instruction:** `n8n-decanter <ref>
  delete` removes a workflow from the server (hard delete, even if published;
  the local folder is kept as the git record). Run it only when the user has
  clearly asked to delete that specific workflow; it prompts for `y/N` and needs
  `--force` to run non-interactively.
- Never use `--force` on push without the user's explicit instruction â€” it
  overrides the drift guard that protects edits made in the n8n UI. (On
  `delete`, `--force` instead means "skip the confirmation" â€” same rule: only
  on an explicit instruction.)
